By Liu Chang and Chen Xiao

How to deal with a large number of suspected patients under the challenge of "back to Beijing tide" ?

The flow of people returning to Beijing after the Spring Festival is a challenge to Beijing's epidemic prevention. As the epidemic has spread across the country, and the emergence of third and fourth-generation infected, other areas outside Hubei returned to the Beijing people are in the prevention and control within the scope. According to the Beijing Population Blue Book: Beijing Population Development Report (2018) , Chaoyang District and Haidian District have the largest number of permanent residents, accounting for nearly 40 percent of the total migrant population in Beijing.

Li Li is in charge of a street in Beijing, a large street with tens of thousands of families. "according to the General Law of the incubation period, people in our platoon were pushed back two weeks from January 21 when the Wuhan epidemic became serious, and people who had visited Hubei Province since January 7 were asked to report their body temperature every day, to isolate themselves and to stay indoors as much as possible. Wear a mask even when you go out and don't take public transport."

Expedition photography

There are no confirmed cases on Li Li's street, but there are "close contacts" , people who have come into contact with confirmed cases. "For this group of people, the streets and the public security work together to monitor them. In principle, we are absolutely not allowed to go out, and we concentrate on purchasing and distributing the goods we need. "

Li Li speculated that the next step may be more streets within the community to carry out closed, semi-closed management, reduce the flow of people to deal with the epidemic period. But if the measures are implemented, the need for "man-to-man" management. But many of the old community does not have property, and previously can mobilize the street volunteers for the elderly, is not suitable for the outbreak of activities outside. "Manpower could be a problem, " Li worries

An important juncture in the evolution of the epidemic in Beijing was January 25, when for the first time a patient with no history of exposure to Hubei Province was notified of the epidemic. The case was highlighted in an interview with the Financial Times by Peking University First Hospital, Chief of the division of respiratory and critical care medicine. The case "means that Beijing's prevention and control strategy should be ready to change at any time, " he wrote, "to prevent a Kalanchoe Pinnata of the virus and a second Wuhan. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By "Kalanchoe Pinnata, " I mean that a large number of new cases are no longer imported cases, but local cases. The increase in local cases means there is a risk of community transmission. In 2003, Beijing learned the hard way. "SARS first broke out in Guangdong and was brought to Beijing by a super-spreader, causing a very serious outbreak in the Kalanchoe Pinnata. At present, one or two cases do not explain the problem, but we should pay close attention to the change of this number, once the increase, prevention and control can not only focus on people from Hubei,"Wang told the Financial Times.

On January 27, the Health Commission released the fourth edition of the "COVID-19 pneumonia diagnosis and treatment program, " Wang's warning was reflected. Regarding the judgment of the suspected patients, in addition to the relationship with Hubei, exposure to "other areas with ongoing local transmission" within 14 days prior to fever and "with clustered onset or epidemiological association with COVID-19 infection" were also added. In Layman's terms, the former refers to traveling or living in an area where there are three or four generations of infected people (patients with no history of contact in Hubei) , while the latter refers to having a concurrent fever among those close to them or having contact with infected people. Well, that narrows it down.

In December 2019, hospitals in Beijing began paying attention

But it also poses a new problem —— As the number of suspected cases that need to be diagnosed may increase.

One of the characteristics of new coronavirus pneumonia in early 2020 is that there are many suspects and relatively few confirmed cases. One is that knowledge of the virus is incomplete. From the uncertainty of "human-to-human transmission" , to the determination of "human-to-human transmission" , to the emergence of asymptomatic infection, the spread of the virus and the means of transmission has been expanding, leading to a large increase in the suspected range. Add to this the fact that winter is already a high season for respiratory tract infection, and that patients with common viral pneumonia, bacterial pneumonia, influenza and COVID-19 are mixed together, and the way the test kit is used for diagnosis is because of the high sensitivity, you have to run it twice to get a result. As a result, the influx of suspected patients requires more time and more medical procedures. This presents a considerable challenge to medical space, manpower, and resources. "This is also the reason why it is so difficult to prevent and Control Wuhan now, " Wang told this newspaper.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Beijing now faces a similar challenge. Because of its strong medical resources, coupled with the lessons left by SARS in 2003, Beijing's epidemic prevention and control of a good start. "In late December 2019, when the Wuhan epidemic started to appear, the Beijing Hospital had already issued a notice to alert the relevant departments of the outpatient and emergency departments to pay attention to screening, " Lin An, a respiratory doctor at a Beijing-based Sanjia Hospital, told the Financial Times

But the information released by the Health Commission on January 29 shows that the epidemic is still in a climbing stage, and the number of second-generation cases in Beijing is on the rise. In order to avoid a repeat of the 2003 Kalanchoe Pinnata tragedy, in the short term there is no specific medicine, the best way to win this battle is early detection, early isolation, as far as possible to include suspected patients into the prevention and control system. But will Beijing's medical resources be able to cope with more suspected cases as the epidemic climbs?

Fever Clinic stress

Lin An told the economist: "At present in the fever clinic, we carry out patient screening when the workload is very large. ". Doctors need to take the time to break apart and ask patients about their previous experiences. Not only in Hubei, but if he has been to other areas, he will also have to decide whether the epidemic there was serious during his days there. It is not clear whether there are three or four generations in some areas, which makes it difficult to judge."

Lin An's hospital has only four quarantined wards in the fever clinic. After screening for both epidemiological history and clinical presentation, they would apply to the Centers for Disease Control for a test kit if the patient was still highly suspected. Patients who test negative for the first time will be quarantined here, waiting for a second test. The Health Commission has already issued kits to hospitals that are qualified for testing, such as Union Medical College Hospital and People's Hospital. Lin 'An's hospital will soon receive the kits, which will speed up the process of diagnosis. This may increase the rate of diagnosis and relieve the pressure on the isolation ward.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Beijing has 101 hospitals with fever clinics, each facing a different number of fever patients. In a hospital in Changping District, the isolation ward of the fever clinic has been expanded several times. "It started with the renovation of the intestinal clinic and later moved from a temporary room and a medical examination centre to an isolation ward. The isolation ward is required not to be in the main building, it must be a single building, and the patients must be isolated in a single room, so that they can not be mixed up with suspected patients,"Li Heng, a doctor at the hospital, told scidev.net. In accordance with such requirements, after the reorganization and transformation, the hospital has more than 30 isolation beds, is now full state.

How to reorganize the resources of doctors?

On January 26th and 27th three medical teams from Beijing set off for Wuhan to fight the COVID-19. Two "national teams" , one consisting of 121 medical staff from six hospitals affiliated to the Beijing Communist Party Committee, and one consisting of 40 TCM practitioners from two TCM hospitals. The other is a "Beijing team" made up of 136 medical staff from 12 municipal hospitals. The three teams assembled the backbone of Beijing's 20 top three hospitals in the areas of emergency, infection, severe disease, aspiration and other fields.

Wang also told the Financial Times that once he is discharged from the hospital, he will probably go to Wuhan, where his Peking University First Hospital already has a medical team there. While it is good news to win the battle with a cadre of medical cadres supporting the front line, it also leaves Beijing and all the cities supporting the front line with a problem: how to make use of and reorganize the team of doctors remaining in the city, dealing with a pandemic?

Lin 'an told our reporter, because of the complexity of screening patients, early screening of the doctor responsible for more pressure. In particular, the hospital is also supporting Wuhan "national team" members. "The hospital lost 20 people. In addition to the 13 nurses, the respiratory division redeployed a chief physician and two senior attending physicians, two deputy chief physicians and one attending surgeon from the surgical intensive care unit, and one from the infection control division. Given that there are only fourteen skeleton staff in a department and that there may be a second round of support, we also face manpower constraints."

Li Heng's hospital, a member of the city's medical team, was also tasked with supporting Wuhan. A total of 11 doctors and nurses, who are most directly related to the outbreak, are members of the Department of Critical Care Medicine, infectious diseases, critical care medicine, emergency medicine, general internal medicine and other departments. With more than 30 beds fully occupied, doctors from the medical, surgical and specialist departments of the hospital have been deployed for unified training by the Department of infection to support the work of the fever clinic.

GAP OF PREVENTION AND CONTROL MATERIALS

In recent days, china-japan Friendship Hospital, Anzhen Hospital, Military General Hospital, Wangjing Hospital of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, etc. have publicly issued a public announcement to solicit medical supplies from the community. Li Heng told the Financial Times that his hospital's supplies had been consolidated and could not be collected on demand as they had been in the past. "The N95 mask in the emergency department was picked up every four hours, but now it is picked up every eight hours. To reduce the risk, medical staff wear a surgical mask outside the N95. The surgical mask is guaranteed to be changed every four hours. "

Zhao Juan is a third-class hospital material docking person, she told this newspaper, the hospital sent a total of 10 medical staff to support Wuhan, in line with the principle of no additional pressure on the local, the aid workers took some protective materials to meet their own use. Because the protective clothing usually hospitals use less, their own warehouse inventory is not much, which has become the most "stretched" of consumables. "A suit is not something you can wear all day. For example, once a fever clinic finds a highly suspicious case, the doctor needs to change out of his protective clothing before he can see the next patient. And during breaks, when doctors return from the contaminated area of the fever clinic to the clean area, they take off their protective clothing and go in for a new one-time use."

After helping a patient once in the field, the medical staff asked colleagues to spray their eyepieces with rubbing alcohol and use them as many times as possible under tight supplies. (photo by Takaboshi)

At present, the protective materials in Zhao's hospital can only meet the needs of doctors in emergency department and Fever Clinic. "But some people with coronavirus infection may not have a fever and can not be treated at fever clinics, so doctors in general outpatient clinics such as smoking and Otolaryngology are also exposed to risk, " Zhao said in a daily consumption list for this magazine, if the hospital to meet the use of relevant departments, protective clothing needs 300 sets a day, there are 500 N95 masks, sterile gloves 8500, and so on. Protective items like face masks have expiration dates, and hospitals don't stock up too much when the lines are open. "what the hospital lacks most now is protective clothing, " Zhao told the Financial Times. "there are still 30 sets of protective clothing left, and it is estimated that they can last for three or four days. "

Although there has been no public announcement for help, staff at the Zhaojuan Hospital have been asking friends in their circles if there is a channel for material assistance.

"The epidemic may peak in a week or 10 days or so, but there will be no large-scale increase, " Zhong Nanshan predicted in a cautiously optimistic interview with Xinhua on Jan. 28, it not only indicates that the strong prevention and control measures are working, but also indicates that the "darkness before dawn" is coming to Florida. From the end of January to the beginning of February, it is still the climbing period of epidemic.

(Lin an, Li Heng, Zhao Juan and Li Li are all pseudonyms; intern journalist Zhang Jiajing contributed to this report.)
